                      • Chapter 5 Exercise 1

                      Real-valued functions

                      In the following exercises assume, where necessary, a knowledge of the formulas for differentiating the elementary trigonometric, exponential, and logarithmic functions.

                      5.1

                      A function f is said to satisfy a Lipschitz condition of order α at c if there exists a positive number M (which may depend on c) and a 1-ball B(c) such that

                      |f(x)−f(c)|<M|x−c|α,x∈B(c),x≠c

                      (a) Show that a function which satisfies a Lipschitz condition of order α is continuous at c if α>0, and has a derivative at c if α>1.

                      (b) Give an example of a function satisfying a Lipschitz condition of order 1 at c for which f′(c) does not exist.

                      Solution

                      (a) If α>0, then for ∀ε>0, let 0<δ<(ε)1/α/M such that (c−δ,c+δ)⊆B(c), then whenever |x−c|<δ, we have

                      |f(x)−f(c)|<M|x−c|α<Mδα<ε,x≠c

                      and when x=c, we have 0=|f(x)−f(c)|<ε. Thus f is continuous at c.

                      If α>1, then as x→c,x≠c, we have

                      |f(x)−f(c)x−c|<M|x−c|α−1→0

                      thus f has a derivative at c and f′(c)=0.

                      (b) Let f(x)=|x| and c=0, then |f(x)−f(0)|=|f(x)|=|x|<2|x−0| for any 1-ball B(0), but f is not differentiable at 0 since limx→0f(x)/x does not exist.

                      5.2

                      In each of the following cases, determine the intervals in which the function f is increasing or decreasing and find the maxima and minima (if any) in the set where each f is defined.

                      (a) f(x)=x3+ax+b,x∈R.

                      (b) f(x)=log⁡(x2−9),|x|>3.

                      (c) f(x)=x2/3(x−1)4,0≤x≤1.

                      (d) f(x)=(sin⁡x)/x if x≠0, f(0)=1,0≤x≤π/2.

                      Solution

                      (a) We have f′(x)=3x2+a. If a≥0, then f is increasing on R. If a<0, then we have f increasing on (−∞,−−a/3) and (−a/3,+∞), decreasing on [−−a/3,−a/3]. f has a local maxima at −−a/3, has a local minima at −a/3.

                      (b) We have f′(x)=2x/(x2−9), so f′(x)>0 when x>3 and f′(x)<0 when x<−3, thus f is increasing on (3,+∞) and decreasing on (−∞,3), f has no local maxima or minima.

                      (c) We have

                      f′(x)=23(x−1)3(7x2/3−x−1/3)

                      let f′(x)=0 we have x=0,x=1/7, so f is increasing on [0,1/7), decreasing on (1/7,1], f has a local maxima at 1/7, and has local minima at 0 and 1.

                      (d) We have

                      f′(x)=xcos⁡x−sin⁡xx2,x≠0

                      and

                      f′(0)=limx→0sin⁡xx−1x=limx→0sin⁡x−xx2=limx→0cos⁡x−12xlimx→0−sin⁡x2=0

                      In the interval (0,π/2] we have sin⁡x<x<tan⁡x, thus xcos⁡x−sin⁡x<0, so f is decreasing on [0,π/2] and f has a local maxima at 0, a local minima at π/2.

                      5.3

                      Find a polynomial f of lowest possible degree such that

                      f(x1)=a1f(x2)=a2,f′(x1)=b1,f′(x2)=b2,

                      where x1≠x2 and a1,a2,b1,b2 are given real numbers.

                      Solution

                      If b1=b2 and a2−a1=b1(x2−x1), then f(x)=b1x+a1−b1x1 satisfy the condition. Other cases where the lowest possible degree of f is 2 or 3 can be similarly deduced.

                      5.4

                      Define f as follows: f(x)=e−1/x2 if x≠0,f(0)=0. Show that

                      (a) f is continuous for all x.

                      (b) f(n) is continuous for all x and f(n)(0)=0,(n=1,2…).

                      Proof

                      (a) It is obvious that f is continuous when x≠0, and

                      limx→0f(x)=limx→0e−1/x2=0=f(0)

                      (b) We have f′(x)=2x−3e−1/x2 when x≠0, thus

                      limx→0f′(x)=limx→02x−3e−1/x2=limy→∞2(y)3ey=0

                      and

                      f′(0)=limx→0e−1/x2−f(0)x−0=limx→0e−1/x2x=limy→∞yey=0

                      so f′(x) is continuous for all x and f′(0)=0. Notice that f(n)(x)=P(1/x)f(x) for polynomial P with no constant term, and limx→0P(1/x)f(x)=0 for all P with finite degrees, thus f(n) is continuous for all x and f(n)(0)=0.

                      5.5

                      Define f,g,h as follows: f(0)=g(0)=h(0)=0 and if x≠0, f(x)=sin⁡(1/x), g(x)=xsin⁡(1/x), h(x)=x2sin⁡(1/x). Show that

                      (a) f′(x)=−1/x2cos⁡(1/x) if x≠0; f′(0) does not exist.

                      (b) g′(x)=sin⁡(1/x)−1/xcos⁡(1/x) if x≠0; g′(0) does not exist.

                      (c) h′(x)=2xsin⁡(1/x)−cos⁡(1/x) if x≠0; h′(0)=0; limx→0h′(x) does not exist.

                      Solution

                      (a) That f′(0) does not exist can be seen by

                      f′(0)=limx→0sin⁡1x−0x−0=limx→0sin⁡1xx=limy→∞ysin⁡y

                      (b) That g′(0) does not exist can be seen by

                      g′(0)=limx→0xsin⁡1x−0x−0=limx→0sin⁡1x

                      (c) We have

                      h′(0)=limx→0x2sin⁡1x−0x−0=limx→0xsin⁡1x

                      however,

                      limx→0h′(x)=limx→0(2xsin⁡1/x−cos⁡1/x)

                      the first item tends to 0 as x→0, but the second item has no limit.

                      5.6

                      Derive Leibnitz's formula for the nth derivative of the product h of two functions f and g:

                      h(n)(x)=∑k=0n(nk)f(k)(x)g(n−k)(x),where (nk)=n!k!(n−k)!.

                      Proof

                      If n=1, then

                      h′(x)=f′(x)g(x)+f(x)g′(x)=(10)f(x)g(1)(x)+(11)f(1)(x)g(x)

                      and the Leibnitz's formula is true. Now suppose the Leibnitz's formula holds for h(n), we consider the Leibnitz's formula for h(n+1), first we have

                      (nk)+(nk+1)=n!k!(n−k)!+n!(k+1)!(n−k−1)!=n!k!(n−k−1)!(1n−k+1k+1)=n!k!(n−k−1)!n+1(n−k)(k+1)=(n+1)!(k+1)!(n−k)!=(n+1k+1)

                      and we obviously have

                      (n0)=(n+10)=(nn)=(n+1n+1)=1

                      Thus

                      h(n+1)(x)=(h(n)(x))′=(∑k=0n(nk)f(k)(x)g(n−k)(x))′=∑k=0n((nk)f(k)(x)g(n−k)(x))′=∑k=0n(nk)f(k+1)(x)g(n−k)(x)⏟A+∑k=0n(nk)f(k)(x)g(n−k+1)(x)⏟B

                      Notice that

                      A=∑k=1n(nk−1)f(k)(x)g(n−k+1)(x)+f(n+1)(x)g(x)B=f(x)g(n+1)(x)+∑k=1n(nk)f(k)(x)g(n−k+1)(x)

                      we have

                      h(n+1)(x)=f(x)g(n+1)(x)+∑k=1n(n+1k)f(k)(x)g(n−k+1)(x)+f(n+1)(x)g(x)=∑k=0n+1(n+1k)f(k)(x)g(n−k+1)(x)

                      So by mathematical induction, the Leibnitz's formula holds.

                      5.7

                      Let f and g be two functions defined and having finite third-order derivatives f‴(x) and g‴(x) for all x∈R. If f(x)g(x)=1 for all x, show that the relations in (a), (b), (c) and (d) hold at those points where the denominators are not zero:

                      (a) f′(x)/f(x)+g′(x)/g(x)=0.

                      (b) f″(x)/f′(x)−2f′(x)/f(x)−g″(x)/g′(x)=0.

                      (c) f‴(x)f′(x)−3f′(x)g″(x)f(x)g′(x)−3f″(x)f(x)−g‴(x)g′(x)=0.

                      (d) f‴(x)f′(x)−32(f″(x)f′(x))2=g‴(x)g′(x)−32(g″(x)g′(x))2.

                      NOTE. The expression which appears on the left side of (d) is called the Schwarzian derivative of f at x.

                      (e) Show that f and g have the same Schwarzian derivative if

                      g(x)=[af(x)+b]/[cf(x)+d],where ad−bc≠0.

                      Solution

                      (a) From f(x)g(x)=1 we get (f(x)g(x))′=f′(x)g(x)+f(x)g′(x)=0, so

                      f′(x)f(x)+g′(x)g(x)=f′(x)g(x)+f(x)g′(x)f(x)g(x)=01=0

                      (b) We abbreviate f(x) to be f and g(x) to be g, thus from (a) we get

                      f′f+g′g=0⟹(f′f+g′g)′=0⟹f″f−(f′)2f2+g″g−(g′)2g2=0⟹f″f−(f′)2f2f′f=g″g−(g′)2g2g′g⟹f″f−(f′)2ff′=g″g−(g′)2gg′⟹f″f′−f′f=g″g′−g′g⟹f″f′−2f′f−g″g′=0

                      during the process we use f′/f=−g′/g several times.

                      (c) From the proof of (b) we have

                      f″f′−f′f=g″g′−g′g⟹f‴f′−(f″)2(f′)2−f″f−(f′)2f2=g‴g′−(g″)2(g′)2−g″g−(g′)2g2⟹f‴f′−(f″f′)2−f″f+(f′f)2=g‴g′−(g″g′)2−g″g+(g′g)2⟹f‴f′−g‴g′+(g″g′)2−(f″f′)2+g″g−f″f=0

                      the last step comes from (a) since we have (f′/f)2=(g′/g)2, and

                      −g″g′=−g′gg″g′=f′fg″g′=f′g″fg′

                      from (b) we have

                      (g″g′)2−(f″f′)2=(g″g′+f″f′)(g″g′−f″f′)=−2f′f(g″g′+f″f′)

                      So we get

                      f‴f′−g‴g′−2f′f(g″g′+f″f′)−f′g″fg′−f″f=0

                      which gives

                      f‴f′−3f′g″fg′−3f″f−g‴g′=0

                      (d) From (c) we have

                      f‴f′−g‴g′=3f′g″fg′+3f″f

                      thus to prove (d) we only need to prove

                      (*)(f″)22(f′)2−(g″)22(g′)2=f′g″fg′+f″f

                      Use the result of (b) we have

                      (g″g′)2+2f′g″fg′+2f″f=(f″f′−2f′f)2+2f′g″fg′+2f″f=(f″f′)2−4f″f+4(f′)2f2+2f′g″fg′+2f″f=(f″f′)2−2f″f+4(f′)2f2+2f′g″fg′

                      since

                      4(f′)2f2+2f′g″fg′−2f″f′=2f′f(f″f′−g″g′)+2f′g″fg′−2f″f′=0

                      we have

                      (**)(g″g′)2+2f′g″fg′+2f″f=(f″f′)2

                      Now it is easy to see (∗) and (∗∗) are the same.

                      (e) If c=0, then g(x)=[af(x)+b]/d, then g′=kf′ with k=a/d and g″=kf″, g‴=kf‴, it is easy to see g and f have the same Schwarzian derivative. Suppose c≠0, then we can write

                      g(x)=ac+bc−adc(cf(x)+d)⟹(g−ac)(f+dc)=bc−adc2≠0

                      Let k=c2/(bc−ad), and G(x)=g(x)−a/c, F(x)=kf(x)+kd/c, we have F(x)G(x)=1, also we see that

                      F(n)(x)=kf(n)(x),G(n)(x)=g(n)(x),n=1,2,3

                      which means the Schwarzian derivative of F is equal to the Schwarzian derivative of f, and the Schwarzian derivative of G is equal to the Schwarzian derivative of g. Finally F(x)G(x)=1 means the Schwarzian derivative of F and G are equal from the conclusion of (d).

                      5.8

                      Let f1,f2,g1,g2 be four functions having derivatives in (a,b). Define F by means of the determinant

                      F(x)=|f1(x)f2(x)g1(x)g2(x)|,if x∈(a,b).

                      (a) Show that F′(x) exists for each x in (a,b) and that

                      F′(x)=|f1′(x)f2′(x)g1(x)g2(x)|+|f1(x)f2(x)g1′(x)g2′(x)|

                      (b) State and prove a more general result for nth order determinants.

                      Solution

                      (a) As F(x)=f1(x)g2(x)−f2(x)g1(x),x∈(a,b), thus for x∈(a,b) we have

                      F′(x)=f1′(x)g2(x)+f1(x)g2′(x)−f2′(x)g1(x)−f2(x)g1′(x)=|f1′(x)f2′(x)g1(x)g2(x)|+|f1(x)f2(x)g1′(x)g2′(x)|

                      (b) If {fij} with i,j=1,…,n be functions having derivatives in (a,b). Define F by means of the determinant

                      F(x)=|f11⋯f1n⋮⋮fn1⋯fnn|,x∈(a,b)

                      then F′(x) exists for each x in (a,b) and

                      F′(x)=∑i=1n|f11⋯f1n⋮⋮fi1′⋯fin′⋮⋮fn1⋯fnn|,x∈(a,b)

                      This result can be proved by induction on n.

                      5.9

                      Given n functions f1,…,fn, each having nth order derivatives in (a,b). A function W, called the Wronskian of f1,…,fn, is defined as follows: For each x in (a,b), W(x) is the value of the determinant of order n whose element in the kth row and mth column is fm(k−1)(x), where k=1,2,…,n and m=1,2,…,n. [The expression fm(0)(x) is written for fm(x).]

                      (a) Show that W′(x) can be obtained by replacing the last row of determinant defining W(x) by the nth derivatives f1(n)(x),…,fn(n)(x).

                      (b) Assuming the existence of n constants c1,…,cn, not all zero, such that c1f1(x)+⋯+cnfn(x)=0 for every x in (a,b), show that W(x)=0 for each x in (a,b).

                      NOTE. A set of functions satisfying such a relation is said to be a linearly dependent set on (a,b).

                      (c) The vanishing of the Wronskian throughout (a,b) is necessary, but not sufficient, for linear dependence of f1,⋯,fn. Show that in the case of two functions, if the Wronskian vanishes throughout (a,b) and if one of the functions does not vanish in (a,b), then they form a linearly dependent set in (a,b).

                      Solution

                      (a) We write

                      W(x)=|f1⋯fn⋮⋮f1(n−1)⋯fn(n−1)|=|F1⋮Fn|

                      Use Exercise 5.8(b) we can get W′(x) by

                      W′(x)=|F1′⋮Fn|+⋯+|F1⋮Fi′⋮Fn|+⋯+|F1⋮Fn′|

                      Notice that Fj′=Fj+1 for j=1,…,n−1, and if two rows in a determinant equals, the value of the determinant is zero. Thus we have

                      W′(x)=|F1⋮Fn′|=|f1⋯fn⋮⋮f1(n−2)⋯fn(n−2)f1(n)⋯fn(n)|

                      (b) Without loss of generality, we suppose c1≠0, then

                      f1(x)=−1c1(c2f2(x)+⋯+cnfn(x))

                      this gives

                      f1(k)(x)=−1c1(c2f2(k)(x)+⋯+cnfn(k)(x)),k=1,2,…,n−1

                      thus if we write W(x)=|C1,…,Cn| where Ci=[f1⋮f1(n−1)], we can have

                      C1=−1c1(c2C2+⋯+cnCn)

                      which means W(x)=0.

                      (c) If there exist f(x),g(x) and f(x)≠0,∀x∈(a,b), then suppose we further have W(x)=f(x)g′(x)−g(x)f′(x)=0 whenever x∈(a,b), then

                      (g(x)f(x))′=f(x)g′(x)−g(x)f′(x)f2(x)=0

                      this means g(x)/f(x)=c where c is a constant, thus g(x)=cf(x).
